<br>
First off, hat's off to Gil. Nam was the first war where our troops fought for our country and our country didn't support them...not just the populace, but the government itself denied so many benefits.  We sent young boys over, eager to fight for freedom and brought back burnt-out men, old before their time from seeing things they should never have seen.<br>
<br>
Second.  Thallus, I agree with your post.  We are a nation of other nationalities.  I think that says it all.  My father was in on the liberation of Paris during WWII, from what he described then about their attitude that day and compare it to what we read about today, I'd say they haven't changed, why are we getting so upset?<br>
<br>
I can only hope that our protests and demonstrations don't get out of hand as they did in the sixties.  It was hard coming home from work and turning on the TV to see people getting off the bus in Chicago only to be beat on by police in the heat of the moment or to see four young college students shot and killed for speaking up with over-enthusiasm.  And equally hard watching the war from our arm-chairs.<br>
<br>
The Constitution gives us freedom as a right, it's our responsibility to use it wisely.<br>
<br>
